This is not unusual. It is not unexplained. It is certainly not a new 
phenomenon. I grew up in Virginia and fished and hunted on the James River 
west of Richmond and saw these all the time on my duck hunting trips. They 
form at the edge of the current and a still "eddy" in the river or stream. 
The eddies can be behind large rocks in the stream or because of a hollow 
or cut in the bank of the river or in a drastic bend where the main current 
stays to the outside of the bend. In any case, they form just as the last 
clip shows; starting small and gradually collecting other floating ice that 
get trapped by the eddy. If the temperature is not so cold to cause a "hard 
freeze" the cluster of ice will grow. Once it get's big enough to have some 
weight, the inertia of it's spinning will resist freezing into any 
surrounding ice which is why they can create an edge that looks like it's 
been cut with a chain saw. The edge grinds against the surrounding still 
ice and builds up a slurry of ice that mounds up around either side of the 
gap.

It is interesting to see, especially for folks who don't live around rivers 
in areas of slight freezing weather that may never have seen this before. I 
just don't understand the weird audio at the end of this video!
